WEBVTT

00:24.058 --> 00:26.233
[WAVES CRASHING]

02:18.034 --> 02:19.898
[BIRD SQUAWKING]

03:14.746 --> 03:16.196
[PIGLET SQUEALS]

03:43.257 --> 03:44.741
[GOATS BLEATING]

03:45.363 --> 03:47.503
[CHICKENS CLUCKING]

03:50.989 --> 03:52.991
[DOG BARKS DISTANTLY]

03:57.237 --> 03:59.342
- Hey, Eumeas.
- What?

04:02.449 --> 04:05.003
They want more of those,
more small ones.

04:07.177 --> 04:08.524
If you eat
all the young ones now,

04:08.627 --> 04:10.940
what's going to be left
for next year?

04:11.043 --> 04:13.287
POLYBUS:
We'll be gone next year.

04:13.391 --> 04:16.152
The queen will have chosen
a new king.

04:16.256 --> 04:17.947
You can starve on your own.

04:19.293 --> 04:21.191
MAN 1: Oh, look who's here.

04:21.295 --> 04:22.538
MAN 2: Look, it's the prince.

04:22.641 --> 04:24.125
MAN 3: The master is here!

04:24.229 --> 04:25.541
MAN 4: Our master!

04:25.644 --> 04:27.301
MAN 5:
Come and join us, prince!

04:27.405 --> 04:28.509
Our prince.

04:28.613 --> 04:30.718
Have you found your father?

04:30.822 --> 04:34.032
- Telemachus.
- Give them what they want.

04:34.135 --> 04:36.483
Boy, tell your mother
that shroud she's weaving

04:36.586 --> 04:38.243
will be for her son.

04:38.347 --> 04:40.521
If she keeps us
waiting much longer,

04:40.625 --> 04:42.765
I'll wrap
your body in it myself.

04:43.731 --> 04:45.699
You still think
she'd marry you?

04:45.802 --> 04:47.390
[SIGHS]

04:47.494 --> 04:48.874
What do you think
she does at night?

04:49.185 --> 04:50.186
[LAUGHTER]

04:50.290 --> 04:52.568
She wants what
every woman wants.

04:53.603 --> 04:55.433
She would not shame herself.

04:56.675 --> 04:58.470
MEN: Oh!

04:58.574 --> 05:00.783
I'll cut your throat,
you little bastard.

05:00.886 --> 05:02.371
ANTINOUS: Leave him!

05:05.960 --> 05:06.927
Wait!

05:25.325 --> 05:27.534
Why don't you tell her
to choose me?

05:30.260 --> 05:31.676
I'll get rid of them all.

05:32.780 --> 05:34.679
Get the island working again.

05:38.096 --> 05:39.718
I'll treat you fairly.

05:43.412 --> 05:45.448
You think
you're better than them?

05:48.796 --> 05:50.004
Poor boy.

05:50.108 --> 05:51.592
Don't you know that
if it wasn't for me,

05:51.696 --> 05:53.007
you'd be dead long ago.

05:56.390 --> 05:58.012
I might change my mind.

05:58.116 --> 06:00.360
[BOWL CLANGING]

06:06.400 --> 06:08.160
Why don't you choose?

06:11.992 --> 06:13.614
Why doesn't she?

06:13.718 --> 06:15.513
This island is dying.

06:16.237 --> 06:17.169
Marry one of them.

06:17.273 --> 06:19.758
Anyone! Then the rest will go.

06:20.932 --> 06:23.383
Your mother will never
marry another man.

06:23.486 --> 06:26.627
She will never stain
the honor of this island

06:26.731 --> 06:28.215
and the name of your father.

06:28.318 --> 06:29.803
My father is dead!

06:40.779 --> 06:43.472
We can't live
with those savages anymore.

06:44.231 --> 06:45.405
Which one?

06:46.647 --> 06:48.960
Which savage
shall I give you for a father?

06:52.170 --> 06:55.035
There must be one you prefer.

06:55.138 --> 06:58.590
I will choose when I finish
your grandfather's shroud.

06:59.384 --> 07:01.144
[TELEMACHUS SIGHS]

07:01.248 --> 07:03.353
You've been weaving
for months.

07:03.457 --> 07:05.183
And what good will it do him?

08:15.218 --> 08:17.186
[MAN GROANING]

08:27.334 --> 08:29.060
PISANDER:
Here to marry the queen?

08:30.924 --> 08:33.685
ELATUS: I think
there's enough of us already.

08:44.800 --> 08:46.802
No one would survive
that weather.

09:08.340 --> 09:10.308
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

09:13.518 --> 09:15.106
[GROWLING]

09:15.693 --> 09:17.729
[GROANS AND MOANS]

09:19.351 --> 09:21.595
EUMEAS: Leave him! Leave him!

09:21.699 --> 09:23.217
[DOG BARKING]

09:25.392 --> 09:26.566
Stay.

09:53.593 --> 09:54.835
What about his face?

09:55.353 --> 09:56.319
It will heal.

09:56.423 --> 09:58.149
[GROANING]

10:08.711 --> 10:10.195
[COUGHING]

10:38.189 --> 10:39.811
[WOMAN LAUGHING]

12:00.720 --> 12:02.722
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

12:18.289 --> 12:19.531
Will you eat?

12:19.635 --> 12:21.326
Where... Where am I?

12:22.327 --> 12:23.397
You don't know?

12:26.055 --> 12:27.505
The island of Ithaca.

12:36.445 --> 12:39.172
Take me. Help me.

12:43.348 --> 12:44.418
Outside.

13:30.810 --> 13:32.018
Eat this.

13:35.676 --> 13:37.471
[PIGS SNORTING]

13:50.484 --> 13:51.520
Eumeas.

13:53.902 --> 13:55.593
Why take in a stranger?

13:57.077 --> 13:59.252
Risk their anger?

13:59.355 --> 14:01.599
Because they haven't
turned us into animals yet.

14:09.641 --> 14:11.333
[PIG SQUEALING]

14:19.306 --> 14:20.307
Market?

14:22.862 --> 14:25.071
There's no market anymore.

14:25.174 --> 14:27.521
Anything with four legs
goes to the palace.

14:29.938 --> 14:31.456
Your king is greedy.

14:32.423 --> 14:33.700
There is no king.

14:34.218 --> 14:37.117
He sailed to Troy years ago.

14:37.221 --> 14:38.912
Took the best men with him.

14:40.534 --> 14:41.639
None of them came back.

14:45.919 --> 14:47.852
Who do you serve now?

14:47.956 --> 14:50.510
The Queen Penelope
and her son.

14:54.928 --> 14:57.551
No man at her side?

14:57.655 --> 14:58.898
[EXHALES]

15:01.383 --> 15:04.524
All year they've been
turning up from miles around,

15:05.042 --> 15:06.975
waiting for her to choose.

15:09.460 --> 15:10.495
Has she?

15:11.600 --> 15:12.670
She's strong.

15:13.222 --> 15:14.568
Keeps them waiting

15:15.569 --> 15:17.192
for her husband to return.

15:19.297 --> 15:20.989
We all have a place
in the world

15:22.404 --> 15:23.508
to uphold.

15:26.477 --> 15:27.478
Eat that.

16:34.200 --> 16:36.754
I want to take you back
to the palace, Grandfather.

16:39.619 --> 16:40.723
Palace?

16:42.691 --> 16:46.315
Yes. Mother is there alone
with those men.

16:47.661 --> 16:49.077
The ones who scared you.

16:52.459 --> 16:53.667
Stones.

16:54.979 --> 16:56.187
They are...

16:56.981 --> 16:58.603
so beautiful.

17:15.620 --> 17:16.690
So should I?

17:18.554 --> 17:21.178
Should I go and try
to find my father?

17:23.594 --> 17:25.216
Find if he's dead.

17:28.978 --> 17:30.359
I need to know.

17:32.603 --> 17:35.433
I could sail
to the mainland tomorrow.

17:35.537 --> 17:37.263
The fishermen would take me.

17:40.093 --> 17:41.267
Father?

17:43.786 --> 17:45.650
You lost your father?

17:47.549 --> 17:49.516
Hmm. Poor boy.

18:27.209 --> 18:28.831
Hey! Pig man!

18:45.538 --> 18:47.643
- PISANDER: Where's the girl?
- I don't know.

18:55.996 --> 18:57.274
Where's she hiding?

18:58.309 --> 18:59.517
I don't know.

19:00.311 --> 19:01.554
She can't have gone far.

19:03.556 --> 19:04.488
[GRUNTS]

19:04.591 --> 19:06.352
PISANDER: If it's not
the girl, it's you.

19:06.455 --> 19:07.491
[CHOKES]

19:07.594 --> 19:10.183
I've come a long way.
I'm not going back without.

19:14.532 --> 19:16.362
PISANDER:
I will not get the queen.

19:18.433 --> 19:19.848
But I'll get what I can.

19:20.849 --> 19:21.781
I'll take.

19:23.231 --> 19:25.336
I'll leave my scar
on this island.

19:38.763 --> 19:41.318
PHILETIUS: So they sailed,
princes and kings

19:41.421 --> 19:44.148
from the smallest islands
to the greatest cities

19:44.252 --> 19:46.599
to honor the promise made.

19:46.702 --> 19:48.428
Ten long years
the heroes fought

19:48.532 --> 19:50.741
and covered their names
in glory.

19:50.844 --> 19:53.709
Ten long years but neither
side could claim victory.

19:55.159 --> 19:57.161
Then out of
the forests of Asia,

19:57.265 --> 19:59.232
by the mighty walls of Troy,

20:00.129 --> 20:02.649
Odysseus built
the great horse.

20:02.753 --> 20:04.927
They say it was just a tower
to get them over the wall.

20:05.031 --> 20:07.723
A tower?
Where did you hear that?

20:07.827 --> 20:09.518
MAN: People love stories.

20:13.902 --> 20:18.527
We'd burned all the forests
to keep the winters away.

20:18.631 --> 20:23.498
Epeius built it with the wood
from the ships of our dead.

20:25.396 --> 20:26.846
You were there?

20:28.123 --> 20:29.711
You saw Troy burn?

20:30.884 --> 20:32.196
Yes.

20:32.300 --> 20:34.371
PHILETIUS:
Our King Odysseus was there.

20:34.474 --> 20:36.821
The smartest
of all the heroes.

20:37.615 --> 20:38.996
It's because of him we won.

20:40.860 --> 20:42.275
Isn't that true?

20:42.379 --> 20:43.552
Tell them.

20:47.349 --> 20:48.695
Heroes.

20:55.046 --> 20:56.669
Odysseus was...

21:03.434 --> 21:04.608
He thought.

21:05.678 --> 21:06.644
A trick.

21:09.302 --> 21:12.374
Something to get the army
through the gates.

21:14.134 --> 21:15.515
Some scheme.

21:17.655 --> 21:18.691
Get in.

21:19.899 --> 21:21.763
Shut the gates behind us.

21:23.454 --> 21:24.904
Locked in with them.

21:26.457 --> 21:28.287
Butcher them in the streets.

21:35.052 --> 21:36.053
How tall was he?

21:39.746 --> 21:40.747
Not tall.

21:43.060 --> 21:44.061
Go on.

21:45.269 --> 21:47.444
He got himself up as a beggar.

21:48.030 --> 21:49.273
Rags.

21:49.377 --> 21:51.482
Crawled into the city
at night.

21:53.553 --> 21:56.832
Counted the soldiers.
Listened to the rumors.

21:58.282 --> 21:59.559
Saw the pain.

22:00.249 --> 22:01.768
The market was empty.

22:01.872 --> 22:03.287
People...

22:03.391 --> 22:05.738
People wanted food, clothes...

22:06.773 --> 22:07.774
peace.

22:08.637 --> 22:10.329
The whole city wanted.

22:12.261 --> 22:13.815
The stones wanted.

22:13.918 --> 22:14.988
PHILETIUS:
But the treasures...

22:15.092 --> 22:17.819
And then on the second day
he saw Helen.

22:19.959 --> 22:22.168
The beggars were
supposed to keep in line.

22:22.271 --> 22:23.756
But he stepped out.

22:25.309 --> 22:26.586
Held out his hand.

22:29.140 --> 22:30.659
She looked straight at him.

22:34.007 --> 22:35.492
Put a coin in his hand.

22:37.942 --> 22:39.772
Her escort were mounted.

22:42.257 --> 22:43.845
And that's when
he thought of it.

22:45.467 --> 22:46.813
The wooden horse.

22:49.298 --> 22:51.404
A great wooden horse.

22:54.165 --> 22:57.168
They'll open the gates
and drag it inside.

22:58.756 --> 23:01.828
And in the morning,
it will vomit soldiers.

23:03.174 --> 23:04.762
The city will be dead.

23:12.252 --> 23:13.322
We took our revenge

23:13.426 --> 23:15.394
for all the years away
from home.

23:16.049 --> 23:17.223
For all our dead.

23:17.706 --> 23:19.708
The cold. The hunger.

23:20.744 --> 23:22.297
PHILETIUS: And Troy was ours.

23:22.953 --> 23:24.920
But the city could
never be won,

23:27.129 --> 23:28.717
only destroyed.

23:31.479 --> 23:33.929
We burned it
to the ground and then we

23:35.206 --> 23:37.416
drowned the flames in blood.

23:43.801 --> 23:45.838
They say that
every war will be like it,

23:47.149 --> 23:48.496
till time runs out.

23:51.775 --> 23:53.742
The dead from Troy,

23:53.846 --> 23:55.882
their ghosts
will come and watch.

24:02.993 --> 24:03.959
And my king?

24:05.754 --> 24:07.238
PHILETIUS:
Sailors say he is near.

24:07.342 --> 24:08.516
HIPPOTAS: Where?

24:09.896 --> 24:13.935
If he isn't dead, why doesn't
he come back and take his own?

24:14.038 --> 24:17.041
Doesn't he care
what happens to his people?

24:17.145 --> 24:19.181
He's turned this island
into a grave.

24:19.285 --> 24:21.908
- He brought glory to our land.
- [CHUCKLES] Glory?

24:22.012 --> 24:24.842
You think that's what
feeds our widows?

24:24.946 --> 24:27.086
Wouldn't they rather
their men back?

24:28.190 --> 24:29.675
Ask my mother.

24:33.472 --> 24:35.163
Well, have faith.

24:35.266 --> 24:37.545
He will return
and slaughter those bastards

24:37.648 --> 24:38.787
and the island
will live again.

24:38.891 --> 24:40.548
Even if he swum
all the way from Troy,

24:40.651 --> 24:42.688
he would have been back
years ago.

24:43.205 --> 24:44.379
No.

24:45.035 --> 24:47.969
He is at the bottom
of the sea.

24:49.557 --> 24:52.042
And maybe it's better
for him that way.

24:58.566 --> 25:00.878
Is the father still alive?

25:00.982 --> 25:02.293
The old king?

25:03.294 --> 25:04.433
Yes.

25:04.848 --> 25:06.297
But mad with grief.

25:08.921 --> 25:10.025
And the boy?

25:10.129 --> 25:12.994
EUMEAS: He's not a boy.
He's a man now.

25:13.097 --> 25:14.547
Little runt. Coward.

25:14.651 --> 25:15.790
EUMEAS: Cowards run.

25:18.447 --> 25:19.966
What can he do on his own?

25:21.002 --> 25:23.245
- Would you help him?
- That's not my job.

25:23.867 --> 25:25.247
Would he die for me?

25:31.426 --> 25:33.497
What does he do?

25:33.601 --> 25:35.637
Hide behind
his mother's skirts?

26:44.775 --> 26:45.845
What are you doing here?

26:45.949 --> 26:47.260
Where have you been?

26:49.538 --> 26:50.919
Where have you been?

26:52.127 --> 26:53.128
Why do you ask?

26:55.027 --> 26:57.098
Are you quarrelling again?

26:57.201 --> 26:58.271
Look at her.

26:58.893 --> 27:01.240
She's afraid. Ashamed.

27:02.379 --> 27:04.346
You know
what they say about you.

27:07.177 --> 27:08.316
Whore.

27:34.583 --> 27:36.309
[GOAT BLEATING]

28:31.433 --> 28:32.400
Where is my son?

28:35.299 --> 28:36.266
Your son?

28:37.716 --> 28:39.200
Why?

28:39.303 --> 28:40.615
Have you lost him?

28:40.719 --> 28:41.961
Where is he?

28:43.100 --> 28:44.515
Telemachus is a grown man.

28:44.619 --> 28:45.620
If he is not in his bed,

28:45.724 --> 28:47.864
perhaps he has found
comfort elsewhere.

28:47.967 --> 28:49.866
We don't all like
to sleep alone.

28:55.216 --> 28:56.355
Please leave.

29:07.849 --> 29:08.885
Don't you see?

29:08.988 --> 29:10.265
The more you keep him
under your skirts,

29:10.369 --> 29:11.301
the more he hates you.

29:11.404 --> 29:13.717
If I let him out of my sight,
they'll kill him.

29:13.821 --> 29:16.271
If you had chosen,
he would be safe.

29:18.757 --> 29:20.241
You will find him for me.

29:21.069 --> 29:23.071
Your son has deserted you.

29:26.834 --> 29:29.008
Your husband is dead.

29:30.251 --> 29:32.460
You are alone. You need me.

29:38.846 --> 29:42.056
You will find him
and bring him back to me.

29:47.406 --> 29:48.372
Yes...

29:50.823 --> 29:51.997
my queen.

30:16.159 --> 30:18.955
We agreed
you'd keep watch on the boy.

30:19.058 --> 30:21.336
He must have gone
to the mainland for news.

30:22.130 --> 30:23.614
The grandfather will know.

30:25.616 --> 30:27.204
He might come back with help.

30:29.068 --> 30:30.759
He might not come back at all.

30:30.863 --> 30:32.175
[CHUCKLES]

30:33.590 --> 30:36.144
These are dangerous waters
this time of year.

30:37.974 --> 30:40.217
Killing the son
won't win you the mother.

30:43.255 --> 30:44.532
Careful now.

30:45.429 --> 30:47.121
There was no talk
of killing here.

31:03.827 --> 31:06.002
[INSECTS TRILLING]

31:23.260 --> 31:24.227
[GRUNTS]

31:25.228 --> 31:27.575
- Get away!
- [WOMAN GROANS]

31:27.678 --> 31:30.164
- Where's the Prince gone?
- No!

31:31.890 --> 31:33.339
Is he coming back?

31:34.202 --> 31:35.307
No.

31:59.124 --> 32:01.126
The old one asks to see you.

32:05.199 --> 32:06.925
You've found my son?

32:09.237 --> 32:11.239
The old king is dead.

32:16.762 --> 32:17.728
I'm leaving.

32:18.971 --> 32:20.697
All the decent men are going.

32:20.800 --> 32:22.354
Only the scoundrels
will be left.

32:22.457 --> 32:24.666
And they're just here
for your wealth.

32:25.219 --> 32:26.737
How did he die?

32:27.704 --> 32:29.154
Old men die.

32:31.984 --> 32:33.675
You need protection,

32:33.779 --> 32:36.437
just as your son
needs a father.

32:38.025 --> 32:40.234
I'm not young
like some of the others.

32:40.337 --> 32:43.133
I'm not famous
like your husband.

32:43.237 --> 32:46.688
If he were alive,
I would respect him...

32:47.724 --> 32:49.657
just as I respect his widow.

32:51.245 --> 32:53.247
I am Odysseus's wife.

32:54.834 --> 32:56.353
Odysseus is dead.

32:56.457 --> 32:57.596
Not to me.

33:02.014 --> 33:04.189
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

33:35.392 --> 33:37.532
There'll be a funeral at dawn.

33:40.052 --> 33:41.605
The old king.

33:42.951 --> 33:45.161
He waited
for his son to return.

33:45.920 --> 33:48.095
Then he gave up hope.

33:51.339 --> 33:53.065
And now he's dead.

33:57.966 --> 34:00.072
Will the family bury him?

34:01.522 --> 34:03.524
The queen will bury him alone.

34:04.766 --> 34:06.216
The son is gone.

34:09.461 --> 34:11.704
That's what our lives
have become.

34:13.465 --> 34:15.846
When I die,
they won't even bury me.

34:18.021 --> 34:19.574
They'll leave me for the dogs.

35:44.038 --> 35:45.350
Now you can choose.

35:46.454 --> 35:47.869
POLYBUS: If you don't choose,

35:47.973 --> 35:49.837
you'll be carried here
in a year.

35:51.114 --> 35:53.599
- I will choose soon.
- PISANDER: When?

35:54.497 --> 35:55.912
POLYBUS: When?
LEODES: When?

35:56.015 --> 35:57.155
Now!

36:00.261 --> 36:02.194
When I've finished the cloth.

36:02.988 --> 36:04.610
She's lying again.

36:04.714 --> 36:08.062
She said that
she was weaving his shroud.

36:08.166 --> 36:10.582
It's too late. He's dead.

36:13.101 --> 36:15.759
The shroud will be
my wedding cloak.

36:17.761 --> 36:20.178
Let me mourn
the old king in peace.

36:21.938 --> 36:23.388
Then I will choose.

36:24.251 --> 36:26.529
There will be no more waiting.

36:51.416 --> 36:52.831
Take me to the palace.

36:53.521 --> 36:55.213
They won't let you in.

36:56.524 --> 36:59.424
They'll think you're another
one hoping to marry her.

37:00.494 --> 37:02.737
Even the tramps
are turning up now.

37:05.153 --> 37:06.362
Take me.

38:01.589 --> 38:03.729
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

38:36.417 --> 38:38.626
[LAUGHTER]

38:57.542 --> 38:59.682
The master's hunting dog.

38:59.785 --> 39:01.511
Stays there, watching for him.

39:02.340 --> 39:03.651
All these years.

39:04.928 --> 39:06.102
Argos.

39:14.317 --> 39:16.595
[ARGOS WHIMPERING]

39:28.124 --> 39:29.436
[WHIMPERS]

40:22.316 --> 40:24.491
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

40:26.562 --> 40:28.218
[DOG BARKING]

40:35.536 --> 40:37.193
A soldier could kill them now.

40:37.296 --> 40:39.471
[LAUGHING]

40:42.336 --> 40:43.855
They wouldn't even know.

41:07.188 --> 41:10.157
LEOCRITUS: Stick with me.
Things will change.

41:11.054 --> 41:15.369
Spare some food for a soldier
who fought at Troy?

41:15.473 --> 41:18.752
Amazing. Another veteran.

41:18.855 --> 41:19.960
A tramp!

41:20.063 --> 41:21.582
[LAUGHTER]

41:24.378 --> 41:25.552
Throw him out.

41:28.693 --> 41:30.522
CTESIPPUS:
Everyone fought at Troy!

41:30.626 --> 41:31.937
MAN: Yes! Everyone.

41:32.041 --> 41:34.733
Some of them
before they were born. Huh.

41:35.493 --> 41:37.046
Here, old soldier.

41:37.149 --> 41:39.289
Let him be! Here, old man.

41:40.705 --> 41:42.085
MAN 2: Enough! Stop it!

41:42.189 --> 41:43.949
PISANDER: Talk to the queen.
Tell her you knew her husband.

41:44.053 --> 41:46.849
ELATUS: She'll screw you
harder than the Trojans did.

41:49.852 --> 41:51.785
PISANDER: Hey, beggar.
Come here.

41:53.131 --> 41:54.166
See him?

41:55.685 --> 41:57.376
That's Antinous.

41:57.480 --> 41:59.482
He's desperate
to get the queen.

41:59.586 --> 42:02.554
He doesn't even want
her wealth. He wants her.

42:02.658 --> 42:04.936
Go and annoy him.
He'll pay you to go away.

42:05.039 --> 42:06.524
[ELATUS CHUCKLES]

42:09.596 --> 42:11.563
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATION]

42:15.360 --> 42:17.914
Something for an old soldier?

42:18.018 --> 42:20.020
Take your rags out
with the other beggars.

42:20.123 --> 42:22.332
You sit
at another man's table,

42:23.299 --> 42:25.163
eat another man's food,

42:26.060 --> 42:29.305
refuse a poor man
a scrap of meat.

42:33.585 --> 42:35.725
Someone rid us of this beggar.

42:36.588 --> 42:38.486
[DOG BARKING]

42:38.590 --> 42:40.868
Here.
I'll show you the way out.

42:40.972 --> 42:43.388
EURYMACHUS: Wait, wait.

42:43.491 --> 42:46.080
We could do
with some entertainment.

42:46.184 --> 42:47.185
Can he fight?

42:47.910 --> 42:50.084
Thank you. I'll go.

42:50.188 --> 42:51.776
Don't go.

42:51.879 --> 42:54.088
You say you were at Troy.

42:54.192 --> 42:55.331
Show us how to fight.

42:56.332 --> 42:57.678
Some of them need a lesson.

42:57.782 --> 42:59.369
- MAN: Come on then.
- Let's see him fight.

42:59.473 --> 43:01.855
- MAN 2: Sit on him!
- [LAUGHTER]

43:05.652 --> 43:07.343
- MAN 3: Go on then.
- Go on.

43:10.346 --> 43:11.312
MAN 4: Come on!

43:12.762 --> 43:13.901
EURYMACHUS: Come on.

43:14.005 --> 43:16.007
[CHEERING]

43:21.219 --> 43:22.392
[CROWD EXCLAIMS]

43:24.118 --> 43:25.085
Is that enough?

43:26.500 --> 43:27.743
[ALL CHEERING]

43:29.745 --> 43:30.918
Get up!

43:33.127 --> 43:35.371
- [DOOR OPENS]
- [CROWD CHEERING]

43:35.474 --> 43:36.752
What is that noise?

43:39.444 --> 43:41.929
Fighting.
A stranger this time.

43:42.999 --> 43:45.277
He might know of Telemachus.

43:45.381 --> 43:47.038
No. He's a tramp.

43:47.141 --> 43:48.729
Don't go there.

43:48.833 --> 43:51.732
He's just another one
who says he was at Troy.

43:53.803 --> 43:55.356
[CROWD CHEERING]

43:56.219 --> 43:58.428
Stop this.
They've had their fun.

43:58.532 --> 44:00.845
[CROWD LAUGHING]

44:02.260 --> 44:03.295
MAN: Hit him!

44:04.055 --> 44:05.056
[GROANS]

44:08.266 --> 44:10.061
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

44:11.614 --> 44:12.788
Stop it!

44:13.202 --> 44:14.237
[GROANS]

44:18.794 --> 44:20.105
[CROWD GASP]

44:22.556 --> 44:25.732
[DOG BARKING]

44:52.275 --> 44:53.760
Someone clean this up.

44:56.521 --> 44:58.385
You fight well for a beggar.

44:59.662 --> 45:01.560
If you're looking
for someone to serve,

45:01.664 --> 45:03.839
I'm always looking for slaves.

45:13.296 --> 45:15.057
[MAN LAUGHING]

45:17.231 --> 45:18.888
EUMEAS: You should be pleased.

45:20.165 --> 45:22.064
He won't need killing again.

45:25.515 --> 45:28.484
Killing a man to amuse thugs?

45:28.587 --> 45:31.418
EUMEAS: He had his chances.
You can't be blamed.

45:36.803 --> 45:39.288
The war, you should forget it.

45:39.391 --> 45:40.427
It was years ago.

45:41.324 --> 45:42.429
A long way off.

45:45.777 --> 45:47.261
It's everywhere.

45:48.124 --> 45:50.989
It's everything
we see and touch.

45:52.059 --> 45:54.855
A cup, the war, a table.

45:56.098 --> 45:57.927
The war. Everything.

45:58.997 --> 46:00.758
Waiting for me to

46:01.897 --> 46:03.450
make it happen again.

46:09.628 --> 46:11.769
What are you
going to tell the queen?

46:15.462 --> 46:16.843
Don't lie to her.

46:17.567 --> 46:19.224
She's suffered enough.

46:27.888 --> 46:30.028
[WIND BLOWING]

46:37.380 --> 46:38.796
[GRUNTS]

46:43.214 --> 46:44.249
Look at him.

46:46.527 --> 46:48.944
That's what happens
to the great warriors.

46:58.470 --> 47:01.577
Get out!
Out with the other beggars.

47:01.680 --> 47:03.061
You can't stay here.

47:03.165 --> 47:04.373
PENELOPE: Leave him.

47:05.684 --> 47:07.169
I want to talk to him.

47:32.435 --> 47:34.299
Come nearer the light.

47:41.686 --> 47:42.929
Closer.

47:43.584 --> 47:44.965
Let me see you.

47:47.243 --> 47:50.246
My nurse tells me
you were at Troy. Is it true?

47:54.561 --> 47:55.527
Yes.

47:56.874 --> 47:58.599
You fought with my husband?

48:03.397 --> 48:04.364
Yes.

48:06.366 --> 48:08.264
Then you remember him well.

48:10.232 --> 48:12.337
It was a long time ago.

48:50.203 --> 48:51.687
Where have you been

48:52.964 --> 48:54.690
since you left Troy?

48:57.244 --> 48:59.971
Traveling. Drifting.

49:07.323 --> 49:09.981
Did you hear of my husband
in your travels?

49:20.958 --> 49:22.235
He must be dead.

49:35.386 --> 49:38.216
The man who left
would never have stayed away.

49:41.668 --> 49:42.772
From his son.

49:46.984 --> 49:48.226
His wife.

49:51.609 --> 49:52.679
His people.

49:58.719 --> 50:00.238
Perhaps he's afraid.

50:03.172 --> 50:04.553
Why should he be?

50:10.766 --> 50:12.078
Perhaps...

50:15.598 --> 50:17.635
Perhaps he is lost.

50:19.568 --> 50:20.638
Lost?

50:24.780 --> 50:25.781
Lost?

50:28.335 --> 50:31.476
How can men find a war
but not find their way home?

50:36.309 --> 50:40.209
For some, war becomes home.

50:56.398 --> 50:58.607
Why do men go to war?

50:59.987 --> 51:02.093
Why do they burn
other people's houses?

51:02.197 --> 51:03.370
Why do they rape?

51:03.474 --> 51:06.304
Why do they murder
women and children?

51:07.305 --> 51:09.721
Aren't they happy
with their own family?

51:17.350 --> 51:19.076
Did my husband rape?

51:24.322 --> 51:26.704
Did he murder
women and children?

51:42.375 --> 51:44.239
This land is ruined.

51:44.998 --> 51:46.413
I sacrificed it.

51:47.552 --> 51:48.519
For him.

51:51.280 --> 51:53.179
My son hates me.

51:57.148 --> 51:58.598
He wants me to marry.

51:59.737 --> 52:01.256
Should I marry? Tell me?

52:01.946 --> 52:03.258
Put an end to it?

52:06.606 --> 52:07.607
Tell me.

52:10.057 --> 52:12.439
Has all this waiting been
for nothing?

52:15.511 --> 52:17.272
[CLAPS]

52:17.375 --> 52:19.757
- [DOOR OPENS]
- Tend to this man

52:19.860 --> 52:21.552
then send him away.

52:53.273 --> 52:55.448
[GRUNTING]

53:12.741 --> 53:14.605
[SOBBING]

53:34.280 --> 53:36.627
Are you scared
of an old nurse?

53:38.560 --> 53:40.976
I washed men
when they were little...

53:43.461 --> 53:45.670
and when they
brought them in dead.

53:47.224 --> 53:48.984
I can wash a tramp.

54:02.687 --> 54:03.826
That scar...

54:06.726 --> 54:08.935
I washed it when it was made.

54:10.695 --> 54:12.870
You came in from the hunt.

54:12.973 --> 54:14.458
Shh.

54:15.390 --> 54:16.701
My boy.

54:18.220 --> 54:20.843
My boy, my boy, you're back!

54:23.121 --> 54:24.468
- No.
- My king.

54:24.571 --> 54:25.814
- No. No.
- I must tell her.

54:26.608 --> 54:27.919
- I must tell her!
- No!

54:28.575 --> 54:29.887
Ow!

54:29.990 --> 54:31.785
[MUFFLED SCREAMING]

54:31.889 --> 54:34.547
Not a word. Do you swear?

54:36.238 --> 54:37.412
Swear.

54:38.413 --> 54:39.690
Not a word.

54:43.072 --> 54:44.039
Yes.

54:48.181 --> 54:49.734
I understand.

54:51.909 --> 54:55.084
We mustn't tell her.
She's not strong like us.

54:58.295 --> 55:00.538
My boy is back.

55:03.679 --> 55:04.680
Now...

55:05.957 --> 55:07.338
you can kill them all.

56:00.736 --> 56:01.703
Father.

56:11.678 --> 56:14.371
We didn't know.
The dead are the lucky ones.

56:17.339 --> 56:18.720
You survive...

56:21.481 --> 56:24.519
but there's
nothing left inside.

56:28.385 --> 56:30.456
All those I left behind.

56:34.460 --> 56:36.185
I can't even see their faces.

56:42.744 --> 56:44.918
I will never be forgiven.

56:53.755 --> 56:56.136
- [BIRDS CHIRPING]
- [GOATS BLEATING]

57:02.039 --> 57:03.005
A boat!

57:04.938 --> 57:06.008
A boat!

57:07.941 --> 57:09.529
- The prince is back!
- MAN 1: What?

57:09.633 --> 57:10.599
MAN 2: The prince?

57:10.703 --> 57:12.014
MAN 3: The prince is back?

57:12.118 --> 57:15.052
A gang of them was waiting
for us at the northern point.

57:15.155 --> 57:18.504
But our fishermen fooled them,
took the southern route,

57:18.607 --> 57:20.575
against the wind
and left them there,

57:20.678 --> 57:24.130
like stranded fish
gasping on the rocks.

57:24.233 --> 57:25.407
Don't you understand?

57:25.511 --> 57:26.926
They are even
more dangerous now.

57:27.029 --> 57:28.306
You must hide.

57:28.410 --> 57:29.549
What about you?

57:32.759 --> 57:35.521
They won't hurt me.
They need me alive...

57:36.522 --> 57:38.696
at least until I choose.

57:38.800 --> 57:41.147
- And I will not...
- You must forget him.

57:43.977 --> 57:45.496
Think of yourself.

57:46.704 --> 57:48.534
A faithful wife.

57:49.396 --> 57:51.191
Or a deceitful whore.

57:56.921 --> 57:59.855
I have no other choice.
I cannot live another life.

58:04.342 --> 58:06.068
I will send them away.

58:07.138 --> 58:09.900
And I will make this island
our home again.

58:10.797 --> 58:13.282
Mother, he won't return.

58:15.906 --> 58:18.046
I met a sailor
who'd seen him on his travels.

58:21.256 --> 58:23.085
He's been living on an island.

58:25.053 --> 58:26.123
With a woman.

58:27.434 --> 58:29.057
He's been there for years.

58:31.093 --> 58:32.267
I'm sorry, Mother.

58:35.201 --> 58:36.685
I didn't want to tell you.

58:40.965 --> 58:42.035
I'm sorry.

58:49.284 --> 58:51.044
Go to Eumeas.

58:51.148 --> 58:52.390
And what will you do?

58:52.494 --> 58:54.047
[DOOR OPENS]

59:03.332 --> 59:04.886
[SCOFFS]

59:04.989 --> 59:07.302
I thought you were married
to your dead husband.

59:08.199 --> 59:10.547
It seems you are married
to your son.

59:13.377 --> 59:14.620
Go.

59:19.901 --> 59:22.351
If I can't be his father,
that's your fault.

59:23.905 --> 59:25.665
But I will be your husband.

59:29.151 --> 59:30.256
And you'll love me.

59:33.224 --> 59:34.743
You will love again.

59:47.204 --> 59:49.275
If you choose someone else,
I'll kill him.

01:00:33.802 --> 01:00:35.045
EUMEAS: Leaving us?

01:00:39.256 --> 01:00:40.291
Running away?

01:00:45.538 --> 01:00:47.540
Do you think I'm a fool?

01:00:47.644 --> 01:00:49.715
I know who you are.

01:00:49.818 --> 01:00:51.406
All these years
we've waited...

01:00:52.269 --> 01:00:53.822
And you run away?

01:00:57.101 --> 01:00:58.620
I'm a slave.

01:00:58.724 --> 01:01:00.587
If I were free,
I'd fight for what was mine.

01:01:00.691 --> 01:01:02.210
I'd fight for my people.

01:01:04.246 --> 01:01:05.109
What will the people say

01:01:05.213 --> 01:01:07.664
when they see
I have returned alone?

01:01:08.665 --> 01:01:11.184
That I led all their men
to their deaths?

01:01:11.944 --> 01:01:13.670
They will hate you for it.

01:01:14.601 --> 01:01:16.086
So die to protect them.

01:01:17.121 --> 01:01:18.813
Your war isn't at Troy now.

01:01:19.814 --> 01:01:20.987
It's here.

01:01:25.129 --> 01:01:26.372
My prince.

01:01:26.475 --> 01:01:29.271
They said you'd run away.
But you're back, safe.

01:01:29.375 --> 01:01:31.480
TELEMACHUS: Until they come
after me again.

01:01:32.309 --> 01:01:33.448
I'll get the others.

01:01:59.301 --> 01:02:02.339
Any wise counsel
from the queen?

01:02:02.442 --> 01:02:05.825
That woman is making
a fool of you. And of us all.

01:02:06.999 --> 01:02:08.517
And now the son, too.

01:02:09.760 --> 01:02:11.417
I have a proposal for you.

01:02:13.626 --> 01:02:14.834
A hunting party.

01:02:17.630 --> 01:02:18.735
EURYMACHUS: If you don't talk,

01:02:18.838 --> 01:02:21.013
[GRUNTS]
your families will starve.

01:02:21.116 --> 01:02:23.429
They might as well die
with you!

01:02:26.915 --> 01:02:28.503
Tell us where!

01:02:29.815 --> 01:02:31.886
[MUFFLED SCREAMING]

01:02:31.989 --> 01:02:34.405
- Where did the prince go?
- LEODES: Where?

01:02:40.377 --> 01:02:41.827
Where is he?

01:02:45.347 --> 01:02:47.764
Tell me where he is!

01:03:10.925 --> 01:03:13.065
[DOGS BARKING]

01:03:49.446 --> 01:03:51.241
Young man. Hiding. Where?

01:03:53.415 --> 01:03:54.831
ANTINOUS: Pisander!

01:03:57.005 --> 01:03:58.179
[BOTH GRUNT]

01:04:02.804 --> 01:04:03.943
PISANDER: Come on.

01:04:16.369 --> 01:04:17.336
So who are you?

01:04:20.408 --> 01:04:21.374
Nobody.

01:04:24.205 --> 01:04:26.345
Did you tell my mother
you were at Troy?

01:04:30.245 --> 01:04:32.489
If you were there,
you saw my father.

01:04:33.007 --> 01:04:34.249
You must have.

01:04:35.043 --> 01:04:36.251
What was he like?

01:04:38.840 --> 01:04:40.048
A soldier.

01:04:41.808 --> 01:04:43.189
Like any other.

01:04:44.225 --> 01:04:46.054
Were you one of his men?

01:04:51.577 --> 01:04:54.442
Did you leave with him
when it was over?

01:04:57.031 --> 01:04:59.378
Deserted, didn't you?

01:05:00.206 --> 01:05:02.381
Sold your weapons for a whore.

01:05:02.968 --> 01:05:05.004
Isn't that what my father did?

01:05:05.694 --> 01:05:07.455
[DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE]

01:05:10.803 --> 01:05:12.253
- Run.
- What?

01:05:12.356 --> 01:05:14.634
- Run! Hide yourself.
- Don't speak to me like that.

01:05:15.394 --> 01:05:16.567
[BOTH GRUNTING]

01:05:16.671 --> 01:05:18.604
- Stop!
- Stay down!

01:05:28.925 --> 01:05:31.099
[DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE]

01:05:53.950 --> 01:05:55.952
[ALL GRUNTING]

01:06:15.833 --> 01:06:17.318
[STABS]

01:06:40.548 --> 01:06:41.514
What happened?

01:06:46.002 --> 01:06:47.279
Who are you?

01:06:50.144 --> 01:06:51.490
Your father.

01:06:54.769 --> 01:06:56.081
EUMEAS: You must run!

01:06:57.599 --> 01:06:58.842
[YELLS] No!

01:06:58.945 --> 01:07:00.982
Telemachus! Telemachus!

01:07:01.534 --> 01:07:04.054
- Telemachus!
- [DOG BARKING]

01:07:04.158 --> 01:07:05.538
[TELEMACHUS YELLING]

01:07:05.642 --> 01:07:07.126
TELEMACHUS: Let me go!

01:07:08.334 --> 01:07:10.681
You'll both be killed!
Telemachus!

01:07:10.785 --> 01:07:12.407
They're coming to kill you!

01:07:12.511 --> 01:07:14.823
EUMEAS: Go! Get to the water!

01:07:14.927 --> 01:07:16.342
- Come on!
- Go.

01:07:16.446 --> 01:07:18.827
I'll hide the bodies.
Keep them off track.

01:08:04.804 --> 01:08:05.771
Where is he?

01:08:06.185 --> 01:08:07.428
Eumeas?

01:08:08.394 --> 01:08:10.016
He's in the hills
with the boars.

01:08:10.120 --> 01:08:11.397
Where is the boy?

01:08:12.398 --> 01:08:14.228
I haven't seen him. I swear.

01:08:15.643 --> 01:08:16.609
[HIPPOTAS GASPS]

01:08:24.272 --> 01:08:25.791
[DOGS BARKING]

01:08:43.636 --> 01:08:44.637
Go on.

01:08:45.293 --> 01:08:46.605
Yes. Come on!

01:09:07.073 --> 01:09:08.282
[GRUNTS]

01:09:11.561 --> 01:09:12.562
Come on.

01:09:29.130 --> 01:09:30.269
[DOGS BARKING]

01:09:36.033 --> 01:09:37.345
Good boy. Good boy.

01:10:51.488 --> 01:10:53.490
LEODES: They lost it.
They could be anywhere.

01:10:53.594 --> 01:10:55.803
PISANDER: Oh, fucking place.

01:10:55.906 --> 01:10:57.356
LEODES: Let's get back.

01:10:57.460 --> 01:10:58.875
I'm hungry. Come on.

01:10:59.255 --> 01:11:01.498
Come on. Good boy.

01:11:02.534 --> 01:11:04.536
ELATUS: We should have
killed him long ago.

01:11:05.744 --> 01:11:06.952
A hunting party.

01:11:17.894 --> 01:11:19.516
[CLACKING]

01:11:32.184 --> 01:11:33.703
Time to start talking.

01:11:37.465 --> 01:11:39.536
He's not my father.

01:11:39.640 --> 01:11:41.400
Odysseus would have
chased that scum

01:11:41.504 --> 01:11:43.885
out of the palace by now.

01:11:43.989 --> 01:11:47.406
Aren't you your father's
steward when he's away?

01:11:49.477 --> 01:11:50.858
Look at this island.

01:11:52.894 --> 01:11:54.102
A wasteland.

01:11:56.795 --> 01:11:59.418
Gangs of thugs
terrifying the people.

01:12:00.385 --> 01:12:01.800
The barns are empty.

01:12:02.628 --> 01:12:04.768
Houses broken into at night.

01:12:06.391 --> 01:12:09.428
The old king
left to die alone.

01:12:14.847 --> 01:12:16.608
Wouldn't you be ashamed
to look your father

01:12:16.711 --> 01:12:18.748
in the face if he came back?

01:12:20.301 --> 01:12:22.924
I know the people
of this island by name.

01:12:23.028 --> 01:12:25.755
I know how they've suffered
without their king.

01:12:28.378 --> 01:12:30.138
And what happened to his men?

01:12:31.761 --> 01:12:34.729
He would have died
rather than return alone.

01:12:41.115 --> 01:12:42.496
You know who I am.

01:12:43.738 --> 01:12:44.739
Tell him.

01:12:46.948 --> 01:12:48.398
I know who you were.

01:13:01.549 --> 01:13:03.689
[DOGS BARKING IN DISTANCE]

01:13:32.166 --> 01:13:33.409
Close the gate.

01:14:51.452 --> 01:14:54.593
Undoing at night
what you weave in the day.

01:15:09.056 --> 01:15:11.783
You thought you were keeping
your husband alive with this?

01:15:15.372 --> 01:15:16.788
Weaving stories.

01:15:22.966 --> 01:15:23.967
How long?

01:15:26.591 --> 01:15:28.040
I'll give you the time.
Not a day more.

01:15:28.144 --> 01:15:29.317
Then you'll marry me.

01:15:32.286 --> 01:15:33.321
I won't tell the others.

01:15:33.425 --> 01:15:34.564
They won't be
so understanding.

01:15:34.668 --> 01:15:37.325
- And my son?
- Your son?

01:15:39.017 --> 01:15:41.606
Why should I care
about your son?

01:16:29.999 --> 01:16:31.587
I wish I'd never met you.

01:16:34.590 --> 01:16:37.006
I want to leave this island,
but I can't.

01:16:42.563 --> 01:16:44.738
I'll die here
one way or another.

01:17:22.223 --> 01:17:23.777
[WINGS FLUTTERING]

01:17:29.817 --> 01:17:31.819
- [PANTING]
- What happened?

01:17:32.682 --> 01:17:34.960
The queen has decided.

01:17:35.064 --> 01:17:37.791
She's going to choose
one of them today.

01:17:43.831 --> 01:17:45.005
ODYSSEUS: Wait.

01:17:48.456 --> 01:17:49.388
Wait!

01:17:49.492 --> 01:17:51.114
It's too late to come back.

01:17:51.218 --> 01:17:53.082
You can only hurt us.
Go back to your other woman.

01:17:53.185 --> 01:17:55.601
If you go to the palace now,
they'll kill you.

01:17:55.705 --> 01:17:57.258
My mother is going to marry.

01:17:57.776 --> 01:17:59.019
Today!

01:17:59.398 --> 01:18:00.779
One of those pigs.

01:18:02.781 --> 01:18:04.403
And what will you do
about that?

01:18:05.991 --> 01:18:06.958
Nothing.

01:18:07.890 --> 01:18:10.099
She's wasted her life
waiting for you.

01:18:14.966 --> 01:18:16.346
I hope they kill you.

01:18:28.496 --> 01:18:30.982
[METAL HAMMERING]

01:19:09.227 --> 01:19:10.815
POLYBUS: What are they for?

01:19:12.506 --> 01:19:13.749
ANTINOUS: I don't know.

01:19:23.897 --> 01:19:26.037
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

01:19:36.979 --> 01:19:39.153
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATION]

01:20:09.563 --> 01:20:10.564
MAN: Look who's here.

01:20:11.841 --> 01:20:13.015
Uh...

01:20:15.672 --> 01:20:16.846
Not now.

01:20:17.571 --> 01:20:18.537
Later.

01:21:00.200 --> 01:21:02.650
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

01:21:49.697 --> 01:21:51.216
Your waiting is over.

01:21:54.495 --> 01:21:56.704
It has been
difficult to choose

01:21:56.808 --> 01:21:59.431
from men of such
diverse qualities.

01:21:59.535 --> 01:22:01.226
Hey, you. Throw him out.

01:22:03.159 --> 01:22:04.402
He's bad luck.

01:22:04.505 --> 01:22:06.404
MAN 1: It's that beggar again.
MAN 2: Throw him out.

01:22:09.234 --> 01:22:10.856
MAN 3: Who let him back in?

01:22:10.960 --> 01:22:13.411
MAN 4: Throw him out.
MAN 5: Out!

01:22:13.514 --> 01:22:14.653
MAN 6: Throw him out.

01:22:14.757 --> 01:22:15.723
Leave him!

01:22:16.897 --> 01:22:18.588
He's my guest.

01:22:20.038 --> 01:22:21.384
In my house.

01:22:21.488 --> 01:22:22.972
- [LAUGHTER]
- MAN: In your house?

01:22:39.264 --> 01:22:40.886
PENELOPE: In fact,

01:22:40.990 --> 01:22:42.474
I cannot choose.

01:22:44.200 --> 01:22:47.031
The choice will be
in your hands.

01:23:11.365 --> 01:23:12.573
This bow

01:23:13.954 --> 01:23:17.130
was a childhood gift
to my husband.

01:23:17.233 --> 01:23:20.236
He was able to make
an arrow fly through 12 axes

01:23:20.340 --> 01:23:22.514
without touching
any one of them.

01:23:30.522 --> 01:23:33.525
The one amongst you
who can string the bow

01:23:33.629 --> 01:23:36.114
and shoot the arrow
through the axes,

01:23:36.218 --> 01:23:38.151
that man will be my husband

01:23:38.875 --> 01:23:40.360
and king of Ithaca.

01:23:40.463 --> 01:23:42.672
MAN 1: But it's impossible!
MAN 2: Enough!

01:23:42.776 --> 01:23:44.122
Circus tricks!

01:23:44.226 --> 01:23:46.228
Why marry someone
because he can do that?

01:23:46.331 --> 01:23:48.126
What if nobody can do it?

01:23:48.230 --> 01:23:50.163
PENELOPE: Odysseus could.

01:23:51.267 --> 01:23:54.719
Would my new husband
choose to be a lesser man?

01:23:58.861 --> 01:24:00.380
AGELAUS: I'll try.

01:24:00.483 --> 01:24:02.830
[LAUGHTER]

01:24:04.108 --> 01:24:05.350
Go on.

01:24:21.021 --> 01:24:22.643
[LAUGHTER]

01:24:29.064 --> 01:24:30.962
Come on! Come on!

01:24:31.066 --> 01:24:32.826
- Come on!
- [MEN EXCLAIMING]

01:24:34.448 --> 01:24:36.243
You're stringing it
the wrong way.

01:24:56.194 --> 01:24:58.231
- MAN 1: Go on!
- [STRAINING]

01:24:59.370 --> 01:25:00.819
MAN 2: A bit more.

01:25:01.268 --> 01:25:02.752
MAN 3: He can't do it.

01:25:12.693 --> 01:25:13.798
MAN 4: Let's see it.

01:25:16.180 --> 01:25:18.113
- [STRAINING]
- Come on!

01:25:18.216 --> 01:25:19.838
- [YELLS]
- Come on!

01:25:19.942 --> 01:25:21.081
Let's see it.

01:25:21.185 --> 01:25:22.358
Come on!

01:25:24.119 --> 01:25:25.292
[GRUNTS]

01:25:33.335 --> 01:25:35.509
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

01:25:43.690 --> 01:25:46.141
What are you waiting for,
Antinous?

01:25:46.865 --> 01:25:48.384
Too scared to try?

01:26:08.577 --> 01:26:09.543
[BOW THUDS]

01:26:17.206 --> 01:26:18.759
This is another trick.

01:26:25.214 --> 01:26:27.320
She planned it this way.

01:26:27.423 --> 01:26:29.425
We will not be
her fools anymore.

01:26:29.529 --> 01:26:30.530
MEN: Yes!

01:26:30.633 --> 01:26:32.670
ANTINOUS: That bow
hasn't been used for years.

01:26:32.773 --> 01:26:34.534
Even Odysseus
couldn't bend it.

01:26:34.637 --> 01:26:35.880
Yes!

01:26:35.983 --> 01:26:36.950
It can't be done!

01:26:37.053 --> 01:26:38.262
MAN: That's right!

01:26:38.365 --> 01:26:40.091
- Shame on you!
- Lies!

01:26:40.195 --> 01:26:41.368
Tricks!

01:26:42.611 --> 01:26:43.439
Lies!

01:26:43.543 --> 01:26:44.613
MAN 2: We won't be
her fools anymore.

01:26:44.716 --> 01:26:46.891
MAN 3: That's right.
MAN 4: It's impossible!

01:26:46.994 --> 01:26:49.687
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

01:26:49.790 --> 01:26:50.964
MAN 5: Lying bitch!

01:26:51.067 --> 01:26:52.655
I will do it then!

01:26:53.656 --> 01:26:54.968
[LAUGHTER]

01:26:55.071 --> 01:26:56.521
He wants to fuck his mother!

01:26:56.625 --> 01:26:59.248
[LAUGHTER]

01:26:59.352 --> 01:27:02.009
EURYMACHUS: I want to see him
fuck his mother!

01:27:02.113 --> 01:27:03.908
MAN: All right!
Give it a go then!

01:27:09.362 --> 01:27:11.640
MAN 2: Go on then!
MAN 3: Give him the bow.

01:27:21.684 --> 01:27:22.892
ANTINOUS:
Enough of this farce.

01:27:22.996 --> 01:27:24.756
We've wasted too much time.

01:27:25.826 --> 01:27:27.242
- The men will choose.
- MAN 4: Yes!

01:27:27.345 --> 01:27:28.312
Right.

01:27:28.415 --> 01:27:30.348
MAN 5: Yeah. Forget the bow!

01:27:30.452 --> 01:27:33.006
ODYSSEUS:
If the gentlemen are finished,

01:27:35.595 --> 01:27:37.562
I thought I might try.

01:27:37.666 --> 01:27:40.289
It's not every day
you get the chance

01:27:40.393 --> 01:27:42.947
to try the bow of Odysseus.

01:27:53.716 --> 01:27:54.752
My queen.

01:27:56.650 --> 01:27:59.964
Can the bow
make a man of a beggar?

01:28:00.067 --> 01:28:02.518
Get back to your place.

01:28:11.182 --> 01:28:13.357
What does the queen think?

01:28:17.153 --> 01:28:18.431
Give the man the bow.

01:28:19.363 --> 01:28:21.537
[INDISTINCT MURMURING]

01:28:27.094 --> 01:28:29.545
Give your father the bow.

01:29:29.294 --> 01:29:30.779
[SNIFFS]

01:30:05.676 --> 01:30:07.609
Look at the old soldier.

01:33:05.165 --> 01:33:07.305
Is this what you wanted?

01:33:07.961 --> 01:33:10.308
ELATUS: Well done,
old soldier.

01:33:10.412 --> 01:33:12.587
Now leave, before you come
to regret your skill.

01:33:12.690 --> 01:33:14.761
Yes, take your luck elsewhere.

01:33:38.820 --> 01:33:40.511
Old man, put down the bow.

01:33:40.615 --> 01:33:42.168
[MEN GASPING]

01:33:43.583 --> 01:33:45.033
- LEODES: He's gone mad.
- Rush him!

01:33:47.276 --> 01:33:48.312
Go! Now!

01:33:48.415 --> 01:33:49.485
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

01:33:49.589 --> 01:33:51.660
- [GASPS]
- TELEMACHUS: Go! Go!

01:33:53.248 --> 01:33:54.249
MAN: Get down!

01:34:07.572 --> 01:34:09.057
You! Out!

01:34:14.649 --> 01:34:15.857
Out!

01:34:16.547 --> 01:34:18.342
Go! Shut the door!

01:34:20.827 --> 01:34:24.037
ARISTRATOS:
We have to rush him together!

01:34:29.284 --> 01:34:30.250
[GRUNTS]

01:34:42.780 --> 01:34:44.161
[CRYING]

01:34:50.063 --> 01:34:52.928
He's mad.
He thinks he can kill us all.

01:34:53.032 --> 01:34:55.828
- He'll pick us off one by one.
- POLYBUS: Stranger...

01:34:56.483 --> 01:34:57.761
Lower your bow.

01:34:58.693 --> 01:35:00.142
If you are Odysseus,

01:35:00.246 --> 01:35:02.351
no-one can blame you
for your anger.

01:35:02.455 --> 01:35:05.803
We have been reckless
in your home and land.

01:35:05.907 --> 01:35:07.494
But one man drove us.

01:35:07.598 --> 01:35:09.427
Antinous!

01:35:09.531 --> 01:35:12.707
- Yes! Yes! It was him!
- It was all his fault.

01:35:12.810 --> 01:35:14.501
EURYNOMOUS:
He wanted to kill Telemachus.

01:35:14.605 --> 01:35:15.882
EURYDAMUS: It was him! Not us!

01:35:16.572 --> 01:35:17.815
It was him!

01:35:38.698 --> 01:35:40.493
Odysseus,
you know I've been...

01:35:59.719 --> 01:36:01.065
LEODES: He's out of arrows.

01:36:02.687 --> 01:36:03.861
Father!

01:36:04.551 --> 01:36:05.863
[YELLING]

01:37:01.539 --> 01:37:03.541
[SOBBING] Kill me now.

01:37:04.784 --> 01:37:05.992
Please.

01:37:23.596 --> 01:37:24.631
[STABS]

01:37:26.979 --> 01:37:28.256
[DOOR OPENS]

01:37:53.488 --> 01:37:54.627
ANTINOUS: My queen.

01:37:56.940 --> 01:37:58.907
Is this the love you wanted?

01:38:05.603 --> 01:38:08.192
If she had been mine,
I never would have left her.

01:38:21.896 --> 01:38:23.449
It could have been
so different.

01:38:32.285 --> 01:38:33.252
[EXHALES]

01:38:46.092 --> 01:38:47.438
PENELOPE: No!

01:38:49.924 --> 01:38:51.097
Don't.

01:39:00.037 --> 01:39:01.556
- [YELLS]
- No!

01:39:01.659 --> 01:39:02.695
[BODY THUDS]

01:40:35.512 --> 01:40:36.823
Why the tears?

01:40:37.790 --> 01:40:39.550
Your husband is back.

01:40:41.035 --> 01:40:42.622
Your son is saved.

01:40:44.176 --> 01:40:46.178
That is not my son.

01:40:51.666 --> 01:40:53.081
A slaughterhouse.

01:40:57.292 --> 01:41:00.088
After all these years,
holding on to peace.

01:41:00.744 --> 01:41:02.194
That was no peace.

01:41:05.266 --> 01:41:07.233
There was no other way.

01:41:17.381 --> 01:41:18.520
Queen.

01:41:19.176 --> 01:41:21.558
Your son wishes
to speak with you.

01:41:32.120 --> 01:41:33.604
Telemachus, don't.

01:41:34.709 --> 01:41:35.744
Mother...

01:41:37.574 --> 01:41:38.816
I need to go.

01:42:19.823 --> 01:42:20.824
Go to her.

01:42:47.644 --> 01:42:49.853
PENELOPE:
You have lost us our son.

01:42:52.338 --> 01:42:56.446
When he finds out who he is,
he will return.

01:42:58.172 --> 01:42:59.449
So wise.

01:43:01.623 --> 01:43:03.763
How can you bear
to see him go?

01:43:12.047 --> 01:43:13.394
So much blood.

01:43:15.568 --> 01:43:16.535
Yes.

01:43:21.678 --> 01:43:23.300
So many years.

01:43:27.718 --> 01:43:28.685
Why?

01:43:40.006 --> 01:43:41.560
Would you still love

01:43:43.078 --> 01:43:44.908
the man I had become?

01:43:49.361 --> 01:43:50.741
I couldn't return.

01:44:01.856 --> 01:44:02.926
Forgive me.

01:44:07.655 --> 01:44:08.690
Forgive me.

01:44:23.118 --> 01:44:24.741
This is not our bed.

01:44:46.418 --> 01:44:48.351
[YELLS]

01:45:32.222 --> 01:45:33.706
When did you seal it?

01:45:35.087 --> 01:45:36.502
When you left me.

01:46:23.825 --> 01:46:25.551
There is so much
I do not know.

01:46:29.244 --> 01:46:31.074
You do not want to know.

01:46:33.145 --> 01:46:35.043
I need to understand.

01:46:37.460 --> 01:46:39.393
You cannot understand.

01:46:41.118 --> 01:46:42.706
I cannot understand.

01:46:50.404 --> 01:46:51.577
We will.

01:46:56.064 --> 01:46:58.550
Your past will be my past.

01:47:00.379 --> 01:47:01.863
And mine, yours.

01:47:04.970 --> 01:47:06.420
Better to forget.

01:47:09.319 --> 01:47:10.803
We will remember.

01:47:13.150 --> 01:47:15.705
And we will forget together.

01:47:20.434 --> 01:47:21.987
And then we'll live.

01:47:29.166 --> 01:47:30.582
And we'll grow old.

01:47:32.100 --> 01:47:33.205
Friends, again.

01:47:35.379 --> 01:47:36.588
Together.
